  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Write the inequality: x^3 < x^2.\nStep 2: Bring all terms to one side: x^3 - x^2 < 0.\nStep 3: Factor the expression: x^2(x - 1) < 0.\nStep 4: Notice that x^2 is always non-negative (and equals 0 when x = 0), so the product x^2(x - 1) is negative only when x^2 > 0 and (x - 1) < 0. This implies x ≠ 0 and x - 1 < 0, i.e. x < 1.\nStep 5: Therefore, the inequality holds for all x such that x < 1 with the condition x ≠ 0. This gives two intervals: x in (-∞, 0) and x in (0, 1).",
