  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>A square grid on the Euclidean plane consists of all points (m, n) where m and n are integers. Is it possible to cover every grid point in its interior by an infinite family of discs with non‐overlapping interiors if each disc in the family has radius at least 5?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Because the discs must have nonoverlapping interiors, the discs form a packing; in any bounded region, the total area of all discs cannot exceed the area of the region. In particular, if every disc has radius at least 5 its area is at least 25π. This forces an upper bound on the density of discs: the number of discs per unit area is at most 1/(25π). \n2. On the other hand, the grid points form the integer lattice in the plane (density 1 per unit area), and the covering condition requires that every such point is contained in the interior of one of the discs. Hence the discs together must cover all these lattice points. \n3. Now, note that if a disc of radius 5 is placed in the plane its interior (the open disc) can contain at most a certain maximum number of lattice points. One may show by enumerating the integer points inside a circle of radius 5 (points (x,y) with x²+y² < 25) that the number of lattice points in any such disc cannot exceed 69. (This is the maximum possible count by a good placement of the disc’s center with respect to the lattice.) \n4. Given the packing density, the average number of lattice points covered per disc must be at least (lattice density)/(disc density) = 1/(1/(25π)) = 25π ≈ 78.5. That means, on average, each disc would need to cover about 78.5 lattice points. \n5. Since no disc of radius 5 can cover more than 69 lattice points in its interior, one cannot meet the requirement to cover all lattice points. \n6. Therefore, it is impossible to cover every grid point (with the point lying in the interior of some disc) under the conditions stated.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>No, it is not possible.</answer>"
}

