{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Did you know that penguins are able to drink saltwater because they have a special gland above their eyes that filters out the salt?\", \"The new coffee shop downtown has an amazing selection of artisanal teas.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Four points are independently chosen uniformly at random from the interior of a regular dodecahedron. What is the probability that they form a tetrahedron whose interior contains the dodecahedron's center?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Recognize that the question asks for the probability that four random points (from a 3-dimensional convex body) form a tetrahedron enclosing a specific interior point (the center). \n2. A well-known result in geometric probability states that if d+1 points (here, 4 points in dimension d = 3) are chosen uniformly and independently in a convex body, then the probability that their convex hull contains a fixed interior point (often the center) is 1/2^d. \n3. In 3 dimensions, this gives a probability of 1/2^3 = 1/8. \n4. Thus, the probability that the tetrahedron contains the center is 1/8.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1/8</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new coffee shop downtown has an amazing selection of artisanal teas.\", \"For example , it could be 'guessing the color just on your left' or 'if you see an odd number of black wrongfulness hats , then guess black ; otherwise , guess white'.\", \"The new coffee shop downtown has an impressive selection of artisanal teas.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let n > 1 be a positive integer. n people form a circle. Bob will put either a black or a white hat on each person’s head so that each person sees the hats of everyone else but not their own. Before the hats are distributed, Ana gives the group a common strategy. Ana wants to maximize the number of people who guess their own hat color correctly, while Bob wants to minimize that number. Assuming both play optimally and everyone follows the strategy strictly, how many correct guesses can Ana guarantee, regardless of how Bob assigns the hats?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Notice that the problem is a classic hat guessing puzzle with an adversarial setter (Bob) and a prearranged strategy devised by Ana. The goal is to guarantee as many correct guesses as possible regardless of Bob's assignment.\nStep 2: A well-known strategy involves selecting one person to act as a 'sacrificial' guesser who gives a predetermined answer that encodes some global information (like parity) to help the others deduce their own hat colors.\nStep 3: For example, the group can agree to interpret black as 1 and white as 0. One person (the sacrificial individual) can announce a guess that corresponds to the parity (say, the sum modulo 2 of all hats he sees). Although his own guess may be wrong, his announcement provides the others with enough information.\nStep 4: With that piece of information, each of the remaining n-1 people can compute the parity of the hats they see and, using the announced parity, deduce their own hat color correctly.\nStep 5: Since Bob can only force the sacrifice to be wrong by his assignment, the strategy guarantees that at least n - 1 people will always guess correctly, no matter how the hats are chosen.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>n - 1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new coffee shop downtown has the best croissants in the city.\", \"I'm looking forward to trying the new vegan restaurant that just opened downtown this weekend.\", \"947\", \"887\", \"unreal\", \"bump\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let n be a positive integer. Find the largest nonnegative real number f(n) with the following property: For any real numbers a₁, a₂, …, aₙ such that a₁ + a₂ + … + aₙ is an integer, there exists some index i (1 ≤ i ≤ n) for which |aᵢ - 1/2| ≥ f(n).</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Define dᵢ = aᵢ - 1/2 for each i. Then the condition is that a₁ + ... + aₙ is an integer if and only if the sum of the deviations S = d₁ + ... + dₙ equals an integer minus n/2. For any n, if all |dᵢ| < t then |S| < n·t.\nStep 2: Notice that if n is even, then n/2 is an integer. In that case, setting aᵢ = 1/2 (so that every dᵢ = 0) gives a valid sequence with the sum integer and maximum |dᵢ| = 0. Therefore, any positive f(n) would fail because there is a counterexample. Hence, the maximum possible f(n) must be 0 when n is even.\nStep 3: For odd n, n/2 is not an integer. Then for any sequence (a₁, …, aₙ) with integer sum, the sum of deviations S = d₁ + ... + dₙ is a nonzero half-integer. In particular, |S| ≥ 1/2. If we assume that every |dᵢ| < t then we have |S| < n·t. In order for it to be forced that some |dᵢ| is at least t, we need n·t ≥ 1/2, i.e. t ≥ 1/(2n).\nStep 4: This shows that for odd n, any configuration must have at least one i with |aᵢ - 1/2| ≥ 1/(2n). Also, one can construct sequences with all |aᵢ - 1/2| arbitrarily close to 1/(2n) while maintaining the integer sum (by carefully adjusting one term by exactly 1/(2n)). Thus, the largest such guaranteed number is f(n) = 1/(2n) for odd n.\nStep 5: Summarize: f(n) = 0 for even n, and f(n) = 1/(2n) for odd n.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>If n is even, then f(n) = 0; if n is odd, then f(n) = 1/(2n).</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new coffee shop downtown has an amazing selection of artisanal muffins.\", \"An airline operates flights between any two capital cities in the European Union.\", \"Did you know that the average lifespan of a koala is around 10-15 years in the wild?\", \"subscribe to .\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Each flight has a fixed price which is the same in both directions, and for every city, the flight prices to the other cities are pairwise distinct. Anna and Bella wish to visit each city exactly once (they may start in different cities). At every step, Anna always takes the cheapest flight available from her current city to a yet unvisited city, while Bella always takes the most expensive flight available from her current city to a yet unvisited city. Is it true that Bella’s tour will surely cost at least as much as Anna’s tour?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. At every city, there is a set of outgoing flights to the remaining unvisited cities with distinct prices. Hence, at each decision step the minimum (cheapest) flight and the maximum (most expensive) flight are well-defined and the maximum is always greater than or equal to the minimum.\n2. Although the tours (order of visiting cities) are determined dynamically, at each step the decision criterion ensures that Bella, who picks the highest priced available flight, will incur a cost at least as high as that incurred by Anna, who picks the cheapest available flight.\n3. Since the tour cost is the sum of the individual flight costs chosen at every step, and at every step Bella’s cost is at least as high as Anna’s, it follows by summing over all steps that Bella’s total tour cost is at least as much as Anna’s total tour cost.\n4. Therefore, regardless of the starting city or the order in which cities are visited, the claim is always true.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, it is true that Bella's tour will surely cost at least as much as Anna's tour.</answer>"
}

