  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>How many interior intersection points, at which four squares meet, are there on a 12 by 12 grid of squares?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: A 12 by 12 grid of squares requires 13 equally spaced points on each side (since n squares require n+1 points). Step 2: Interior intersection points are those not on the boundary. Since the outermost points are on the border, we exclude them, leaving (13-2) = 11 points on each side that are interior. Step 3: The total number of interior intersection points is the product of the number of interior points along the horizontal and vertical dimensions: 11 x 11 = 121.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>121</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The aroma of freshly baked cookies wafted through the air, enticing the hungry crowd. the cookies are arranged . Did you hear that the new coffee shop in town is giving away free samples of their lavender latte this weekend?</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Suppose there are 100 cookies arranged in a circle, of which 53 are chocolate chip and 47 are oatmeal. Pearl 574 selects a contiguous block of exactly 67 cookies. She wants this block to have exactly k chocolate chip cookies. For which values of k is it guaranteed that no matter how the cookies are arranged, there will be at least one contiguous subsegment (of 67 cookies) having exactly k chocolate chip cookies? Find the sum of all such k.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Label the cookies around the circle, and for every starting position i (0 ≤ i < 100) let f(i) denote the number of chocolate chip cookies in the block of 67 cookies starting at i. Because the cookies are in a circle, there are 100 such blocks. \n2. Notice that when moving from a block starting at i to the block starting at i+1, the block loses one cookie and gains another. Therefore, f(i+1) differs from f(i) by at most 1 (i.e. f(i+1) = f(i) ± 1 or remains the same). Hence, as one goes around the circle, the values of f(i) change at most by 1 at each step. This implies that the set of values attained by the f(i)’s is always a consecutive set of integers: {m, m+1, …, M} where m = min_i f(i) and M = max_i f(i).\n3. The total number of chocolate chip cookies is fixed at 53. Each cookie appears in exactly 67 of these blocks so the sum of all f(i) is 67×53, and the average number of chocolate chip cookies per block is 67×53/100 = 3551/100 = 35.51. Therefore, in every arrangement some block has at most 35 chocolate chip cookies and some block has at least 36 cookies (because if all blocks were ≥36 the total would be at least 3600, and if ≤35 then at most 3500, both contradicting 3551). \n4. Consequently, in every arrangement the set of values of f(i) (which is an uninterrupted interval) must include 35 and 36. In an arrangement that is completely balanced (i.e. where the blocks have only the two values 35 and 36) the set is exactly {35, 36}. In other arrangements the set may be larger, but the two numbers 35 and 36 will always be present. \n5. Thus, Pearl is guaranteed to succeed if she chooses k = 35 or k = 36. \n6. The problem asks for the sum of all such k. Hence, the answer is 35 + 36 = 71.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>71</answer>"
}

