  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>In HMMT February 2017, 679 contestants participated. Let N be the number of these contestants who performed at or above the median score on at least one of the three individual tests. Estimate N.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Assume that for each individual test, half of the contestants score at or above the median (i.e. probability = 1/2).\nStep 2: The probability that a contestant scores below the median on a single test is also 1/2.\nStep 3: Assuming independence among the tests, the probability that a contestant scores below the median on all three tests is (1/2)^3 = 1/8.\nStep 4: Therefore, the probability that a contestant scores at or above the median on at least one test is 1 - 1/8 = 7/8.\nStep 5: Multiply this probability by the total number of contestants: (7/8) * 679.\nStep 6: Calculate 679 * 7 = 4753; then divide 4753 by 8 to get approximately 594.125, which rounds to about 594.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>594</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentences about the new restaurant downtown, the comment about feeling hungry and grabbing a snack, and the extraneous numbers (574 and 464) are irrelevant.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>I have five different pairs of socks. Every day for five days, I pick two socks at random without replacement to wear for the day. Find the probability that I wear matching socks on both the third day and the fifth day.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Note that there are 5 pairs of socks, i.e. 10 individual socks. Over 5 days, you will pick all socks in 5 consecutive draws of 2 socks each, which is equivalent to randomly partitioning the 10 socks into 5 pairs in a sequential (ordered) manner.\nStep 2: Focus on a given day. When two socks are drawn randomly from a set of m socks, if you choose one sock then its matching partner is one specific sock out of the remaining (m-1). Thus, the probability that a given drawn pair is a matching pair is 1/(m-1).\nStep 3: For the third day, before drawing, 4 socks have been removed (from days 1 and 2). So there remain 6 socks. However, by the symmetry of the random process, we can also use the approach of ordered pairing. In an ordered pairing of 10 socks into 5 pairs, the probability that any specific pair is a matching pair is 1/(10-1) = 1/9.\nStep 4: Similarly, by the time of the fifth day, 8 socks have been used on the previous days. Thus, for the remaining pair (day 5), viewing it in sequence, after taking one sock for day 5 the chance that its matching sock is the one drawn alongside it is 1/(2-1 remaining from that mini-set, but more directly following the ordered pairing method, it is 1/(number of remaining socks minus one)). Alternatively, conditioning on day 3 having a matching pair, one can argue that the probabilities for the designated days multiply. Specifically, the probability for the day 5 pair to be a match is 1/7 (using similar reasoning on the reduced set of socks after day 3’s match has been fixed).\nStep 5: Thus, the joint probability that both the third day and the fifth day yield matching pairs is (1/9) * (1/7) = 1/63.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1/63</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Did you know that the latest season of your favorite TV show is now available on Netflix?\", \"The weather forecast for the upcoming weekend is looking quite unpredictable with a high chance of scattered thunderstorms.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let n = 521 be a positive integer. Find all n × n real matrices A (with only real eigenvalues) satisfying A + A^k = A^T for some integer k ≥ n.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Notice that A and its transpose A^T share the same eigenvalues. For any eigenvalue λ of A, the equation A + A^k = A^T forces the corresponding eigenvalue relation λ + λ^k to equal one of the eigenvalues of A (namely λ itself) because A^T has the same spectrum as A.\n2. Hence, for each eigenvalue we have λ + λ^k = λ, which simplifies to λ^k = 0. Since k ≥ n and k is a positive integer, this implies that λ = 0.\n3. Therefore, all eigenvalues of A are zero, so A is a nilpotent matrix.\n4. However, given that A + A^k = A^T and A is nilpotent, note that for any nilpotent matrix of size n, if k ≥ n then A^k = 0. The equation then reduces to A = A^T, meaning A must be symmetric.\n5. The only symmetric nilpotent matrix is the zero matrix (because a symmetric matrix is diagonalizable, and if its only eigenvalue is 0 then it must be the zero matrix).\n6. Thus, the only solution is A = 0.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>The only solution is the n × n zero matrix.</answer>"
}

