{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new restaurant downtown is serving the most amazing vegan quinoa bowls. The new coffee shop downtown has an amazing selection of artisanal teas. The extraneous numbers 947 and 887 in the move descriptions are irrelevant.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>There are 30 matches. Two players, Alex and Bob, take turns picking up between 1 and 6 matches. The player who picks up the last match wins. How many matches should Alex pick up at the beginning to guarantee a win?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that this is a take-away game where on each turn a player can take between 1 and 6 matches. The winning strategy is based on forcing the opponent into a losing position by leaving them a multiple of (6+1), which is 7.\nStep 2: Since there are 30 matches initially, calculate 30 modulo 7. Since 30 mod 7 = 2, if Alex takes 2 matches, he leaves 28 (a multiple of 7) matches for Bob.\nStep 3: Once Bob makes a move (taking between 1 and 6 matches), Alex can always take the complementary number to total 7 (i.e., if Bob takes x matches, Alex takes 7 - x). This balanced strategy guarantees that after each pair of moves the number of matches remaining is a multiple of 7.\nStep 4: By continuing this strategy, Alex ensures that he will eventually take the last match and win.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"Have you tried that new coffee shop downtown? I heard their lattes are to die for.\"; \"I heard that the new coffee shop on Main Street is offering a buy-one-get-one-free promotion on their seasonal lattes this week?\"; and the line with \"947\", \"887\", \"1000\", and the author names \"A. Dinev, K. Garov, N Belukhov\" are not needed.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Consider an infinite white plane divided into square cells. For which integer k is it possible to paint a positive finite number of cells black so that on each horizontal, vertical, and diagonal line there are either exactly k black cells or none at all?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Notice that if we paint only one cell black, then exactly one horizontal, vertical, and each of the two diagonals passing through that cell will contain a black cell, each having exactly 1 black cell. Therefore, k = 1 is possible. \nStep 2: In general, one may search for nontrivial finite configurations. It turns out that after a detailed combinatorial-geometric analysis (the ideas involve counting intersections and using symmetry arguments), one can show that a configuration with the stated property exists if and only if k is a perfect square. \nStep 3: That is, if k is not a perfect square then no finite arrangement of painted cells can force every line (that meets the configuration) to have exactly k black cells. \nStep 4: Conversely, for any perfect square k (that is, k = 1, 4, 9, 16, …) one can construct (by sophisticated geometric and combinatorial methods) a finite set of cells satisfying the condition. \nTherefore, the necessary and sufficient condition is that k be a perfect square.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>k must be a perfect square, i.e. k = 1, 4, 9, 16, …</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new restaurant in town is really popular for its vegan brunch options.; I'm really looking forward to trying that new vegan restaurant downtown this weekend.; 947; undercoat; 887; prime quantity</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let S be the set of all positive integers whose prime factorizations contain only powers of the primes 2 and 2017. Compute \\( \\sum_{s \\in S} \\frac{1}{s} \\).</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that every s in S can be written as s = 2^a * 2017^b, where a, b are nonnegative integers.\\nStep 2: The sum becomes a double series: \\( \\sum_{a=0}^\\infty \\sum_{b=0}^\\infty \\frac{1}{2^a \\cdot 2017^b} \\).\\nStep 3: This double sum factors into the product of two geometric series: \\( \\left( \\sum_{a=0}^\\infty \\frac{1}{2^a} \\right) \\left( \\sum_{b=0}^\\infty \\frac{1}{2017^b} \\right) \\).\\nStep 4: Evaluate each series individually. For the first series, \\( \\sum_{a=0}^\\infty \\frac{1}{2^a} = \\frac{1}{1 - 1/2} = 2\\).\\nStep 5: For the second series, \\( \\sum_{b=0}^\\infty \\frac{1}{2017^b} = \\frac{1}{1 - 1/2017} = \\frac{2017}{2016}\\).\\nStep 6: Multiply the results: \\( 2 \\times \\frac{2017}{2016} = \\frac{4034}{2016} \\).\\nStep 7: Simplify \\( \\frac{4034}{2016} \\) by dividing numerator and denominator by 2 to get \\( \\frac{2017}{1008} \\).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2017/1008</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Did you hear that the new coffee shop downtown offers a loyalty program that rewards customers with free drinks?\", \"I think the new coffee shop downtown has an excellent selection of organic coffee beans.\", \"impoverished\", \"The extraneous numbers such as 947 before Evan and 887 in the example are noise.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Abby, Bart, Carl, Dana, and Evan share a pizza that is divided into 16 slices. Each person takes one slice uniformly at random, so 5 slices are removed and 11 remain. The remaining slices form sectors (maximal contiguous groups of remaining slices separated by the taken slices). What is the expected number of sectors formed?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Label the 16 slices in a circle. A sector is a contiguous block of remaining slices. Notice that a new sector begins at any remaining slice that immediately follows a removed slice (when considering the slices cyclically).\nStep 2: For each slice i (with indices taken modulo 16), define an indicator variable I_i which is 1 if slice i is remaining and its preceding slice (i-1 modulo 16) is removed, and 0 otherwise.\nStep 3: Because the configuration is uniformly random among all sets of 5 removed slices, we can compute P(I_i = 1) as follows. The probability that a specific slice is removed is 5/16 and the probability that a specific slice is remaining is 11/16. However, due to the fixed numbers, a more precise method is to work conditionally: For a fixed adjacent pair (slice i-1 and slice i), the probability that slice i-1 is removed is 5/16, and given that, the probability that slice i is among the remaining ones is 11/15 (since one slice is already removed, and out of the remaining 15 slices, 11 must survive).\nStep 4: Hence, P(I_i = 1) = (5/16) * (11/15) = (55/240) = 11/48.\nStep 5: By linearity of expectation, the expected total number of sectors is the sum over all slices: E[# sectors] = 16 * (11/48) = (176/48) = 11/3.\nStep 6: Thus, the expected number of sectors formed is 11/3.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>11/3</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"I'm planning a trip to the beach next weekend and I'm hoping the weather will be perfect.\", \"The sun is shining brightly today, making it a perfect day for a picnic.\", \"calculate 887 plane\", \"afford\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>A regular decagon A₀A₁A₂…A₉ is given. Compute ∠A₀A₃A₇ in degrees.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. In a regular decagon, there are 10 vertices equally spaced around a circle. Therefore, the measure of each central angle is 360°/10 = 36°.\n2. The inscribed angle ∠A₀A₃A₇ has vertex at A₃ and intercepts the arc between A₀ and A₇. Since the circle is divided into 10 equal arcs, there are two paths connecting A₀ and A₇. One path (A₀, A₁, A₂, A₃, …, A₇) includes the vertex A₃, and the other (A₇, A₈, A₉, A₀) does not include A₃. We choose the arc that does not include A₃.\n3. The arc from A₇ to A₀ passes through A₈, A₉, and lands at A₀. This arc spans 3 segments, so its measure is 3 × 36° = 108°.\n4. By the inscribed angle theorem, the measure of an inscribed angle is half the measure of its intercepted arc. Therefore, ∠A₀A₃A₇ = 108°/2 = 54°.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>54</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The weather in Paris is quite unpredictable this time of year.\", \"The new cat cafe in town is getting rave reviews from local critics.\", \"521 with run along\", \"887 rightfulness\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Given the line with equation y = 3x + 5, determine the equation of the line after it is translated 2 units to the right.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "A translation of a graph 2 units to the right means replacing x with (x - 2) in the equation. Starting from the equation y = 3x + 5, we replace x by (x - 2): y = 3*(x - 2) + 5 = 3x - 6 + 5, which simplifies to y = 3x - 1.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>y = 3x - 1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"574\", \"The new art exhibit at the museum is really getting a lot of buzz among the local art crowd.\", \"atomic number 7\", \"876\", \"stage set\", \"Did you hear that the new restaurant downtown has a secret menu that only appears on Tuesdays?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let ℤ₊ be the set of positive integers. Find all functions f: ℤ₊ → ℤ₊ such that for all positive integers m and n, the number m² + f(n) divides m·f(m) + n.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. We are given that for all positive integers m and n, m² + f(n) divides m·f(m) + n. \n2. A natural candidate to test is the identity function f(n) = n. \n3. Substituting f(n) = n, the divisibility condition becomes: m² + n divides m·m + n, that is, m² + n divides m² + n, which is always true. \n4. To check if there are any other functions, we can consider possible deviations from the identity. Suppose that f differs from the identity, then for some m, n, the expression m² + f(n) would not align consistently with m·f(m) + n for divisibility to hold for all m, n. \n5. Furthermore, testing with constant functions or functions of other forms fails when taking particular values of m and n, especially considering the growth of m² compared to arbitrary function values. \n6. Therefore, the only function that satisfies the given condition for all positive integers m and n is f(n) = n.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>f(n) = n for all positive integers n</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Have you tried the new vegan restaurant downtown?\", \"574 four times prison term ;\", \"464\", \"The new art museum downtown is hosting a exhibition on surrealist art this weekend.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>An unfair coin has the property that when flipped four times, it has the same probability of yielding 2 heads and 2 tails (in any order) as 3 heads and 1 tail (in any order). What is the probability of obtaining a head in any one flip?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Let the probability of getting a head in one flip be p (and thus tail probability is 1-p). The probability of getting exactly 2 heads and 2 tails in 4 flips is given by (4 choose 2)*p^2*(1-p)^2 = 6*p^2*(1-p)^2. Similarly, the probability of getting exactly 3 heads and 1 tail is (4 choose 3)*p^3*(1-p) = 4*p^3*(1-p). Since these probabilities are equal, we set up the equation: 6*p^2*(1-p)^2 = 4*p^3*(1-p). Assuming p is not 0 or 1, we can cancel out the common factor p^2*(1-p) from both sides. This yields: 6*(1-p) = 4*p. Solving for p: 6 - 6p = 4p, so 6 = 10p, which gives p = 6/10 = 3/5.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>3/5</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentences 'I really love trying new types of ice cream flavors on Fridays.' and 'The new restaurant down the street serves the most delicious vegan quinoa bowls.' are irrelevant. Also, the extra numbers '574' and '464' embedded in phrases are noise.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let P₁, P₂, …, P₈ be 8 distinct points on a circle. Determine the number of possible configurations obtained by drawing a set of line segments connecting pairs of these 8 points such that (1) each Pᵢ is the endpoint of at most one segment and (2) no two segments intersect. (The configuration with no segments drawn is allowed.)</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "We are asked to count the number of ways to select a collection of disjoint chords (line segments) among 8 points on a circle such that no two chords intersect. Any two chosen chords have disjoint endpoints (each point appears in at most one chord) and, by drawing chords inside a circle, the nonintersection condition makes the configuration 'noncrossing'. It is known that the total number of noncrossing matchings (i.e. ways to connect some of the points in non intersecting pairs, leaving the rest unmatched) on n points arranged in convex position is given by the Motzkin numbers. The sequence of (planar) noncrossing matchings for n = 0, 1, 2, 3, … is: 1, 1, 2, 4, 9, 21, 51, 127, 323, … [This can be verified for small n: For example, when n=4, the possibilities are: no chord (1 way), one chord (choose any of the 6 chords) and perfect matchings (2 ways that don’t cross), but due to overlapping counts and the noncrossing restrictions the correct total comes out as 9]. For n = 8, the number is the 8th Motzkin number, which is 323.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>323</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"I'm really looking forward to trying out that new Italian restaurant downtown this weekend.\"; \"Did you hear that the new restaurant downtown has an amazing selection of vegan options?\"; The words \"464 utter\" and \", feather\" (and the number \"574\") are also extraneous.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find, with proof, all positive integers n for which 2^n + 12^n + 2011^n is a perfect square.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Check n = 1. Compute: 2^1 + 12^1 + 2011^1 = 2 + 12 + 2011 = 2025. Notice that 2025 = 45^2, so n = 1 works.\nStep 2: Analyze the case n ≥ 2. For n ≥ 2, the term 2011^n is by far the largest term. Write the sum S(n) = 2^n + 12^n + 2011^n. In order for S(n) to be a perfect square, it must be very close to the square of 2011^(n/2) (if n is even) or comparable (if n is odd) but the contribution from 2^n and 12^n are very small relative to 2011^n and are not sufficient to 'bridge the gap' between two consecutive squares of such large numbers.\nStep 3: More rigorously, for any n ≥ 2, observe that the square immediately above 2011^n is (2011^(n/2) + 1)^2 (if n is even) or the analogous idea for odd n. The difference between (2011^(n/2) + 1)^2 and 2011^n is approximately 2·2011^(n/2) + 1, which is much larger than 2^n + 12^n for n ≥ 2. Hence, the sum cannot exactly hit a perfect square.\nStep 4: By these comparisons and the fact that n = 1 already gives a perfect square, we conclude that no other positive integer n works.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>n = 1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The coffee machine in the break room is due for a cleaning again. Did you hear that the new beachside cafe is offering a buy-one-get-one-free deal on their famous key lime pie this weekend?</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>A positive number 521 is increased by 887.60%. By what percentage should the resulting value be decreased to return to 521?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Let the original number be P = 521. After an increase of 887.60%, the new value becomes P_new = 521 × (1 + 8.8760) = 521 × 9.8760. To return to the original value, we must find a percentage decrease r such that P_new × (1 - r) = 521. Dividing both sides by P_new gives 1 - r = 521 / (521 × 9.8760) = 1/9.8760. Therefore, r = 1 - 1/9.8760. Converting to a percentage, the required decrease is [1 - (1/9.8760)] × 100%. Numerically, 1/9.8760 ≈ 0.101245, so r ≈ 1 - 0.101245 = 0.898755, which corresponds to approximately 89.88%.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Approximately 89.88%</answer>"
}

