{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentences 'The new coffee shop downtown has a great selection of seasonal lattes.' and 'I love trying new recipes from my grandmother's old cookbook.' as well as the stray numbers and phrases like '574', '464', and 'atomic number 15' are irrelevant to the math problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find all positive integers m for which there exists a prime number p (with p not dividing m) such that for every integer n the congruence n^m ≡ m (mod p) has no solution.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "We interpret the problem as follows. For a given positive integer m and some prime p (with p not dividing m), we want that no integer n satisfies n^m ≡ m (mod p). A natural first idea is to check the obvious candidate n = m. In that case, the congruence would become m^m ≡ m (mod p). Since p does not divide m, we can cancel m to obtain m^(m-1) ≡ 1 (mod p). Thus, if for our chosen prime p the relation m^(m-1) ≡ 1 (mod p) holds, then n = m is a solution and the condition fails. Hence, to have no solution it is necessary that m^(m-1) not be congruent to 1 modulo p. In more conceptual terms, the mapping f(n) = n^m (mod p) (extended to include 0) covers only a certain subset (namely a subgroup of F_p^*) along with 0. The number m (taken modulo p) must lie outside the image set. Standard number–theoretic results (and Dirichlet’s theorem on primes in arithmetic progressions) guarantee that for any fixed nonzero integer m (other than m = 1, where cancellation is unavoidable) one can choose a prime p (avoiding the finite set dividing m) such that m is not an mth power residue modulo p. (For example, when m = 2 the condition is that 2 is a quadratic nonresidue mod p; by quadratic reciprocity there are infinitely many such p.) Thus, for every integer m ≥ 2 one may select a prime with the required property. Note that when m = 1 we get n^1 ≡ 1 (mod p), and choosing n = 1 gives 1 ≡ 1 (mod p) trivially, so m = 1 fails the condition.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>All positive integers m with m ≥ 2</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"My grandmother's cat could recite the entire script of 'Hamlet' backwards while riding a unicycle.\" and \"Did you hear that the new coffee shop downtown is having a buy-one-get-one-free promotion on all their seasonal lattes this weekend?\"</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find the number of nonempty collections 𝔽 of subsets of {1, 2, …, 2014} such that: (a) for any S₁, S₂ ∈ 𝔽 we have S₁ ∩ S₂ ∈ 𝔽; (b) if S ∈ 𝔽 and T ⊆ {1,2,…,2014} with S ⊆ T, then T ∈ 𝔽.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Notice that conditions (a) and (b) imply 𝔽 is an upward closed family which is also closed under intersections. \n2. In any nonempty family 𝔽 with these properties, the intersection of all its elements, say A, is itself in 𝔽 and is minimal in the sense that every member of 𝔽 contains A. \n3. Since 𝔽 is upward closed, it must consist of exactly all subsets of {1,2,…,2014} that contain A, i.e., 𝔽 = { X ⊆ {1,2,…,2014} : A ⊆ X }.\n4. Every such family is uniquely determined by its minimal element A. \n5. Since A can be any subset of {1,2,…,2014}, there are 2^(2014) choices for A. \n6. Therefore, the number of possible families is 2^(2014).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2^(2014)</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentences about recent rainfall causing flooding in the nearby park and the mention of the new artisanal coffee shop with the best lavender latte in the city are irrelevant. Also, extraneous numbers like '521 n tot' and '887 sum' are non-essential for solving the math problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For each positive integer n, let s(n) be the sum of the squares of the digits of n (for example, s(15) = 1² + 5² = 26). Determine all integers n ≥ 1 such that s(n) = n.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Note that for a positive integer n, s(n) is the sum of the squares of its digits, which for a d-digit number is at most 81d (since the maximum square of a digit is 9² = 81).\nStep 2: For n with more than one digit, n will be at least 10, but s(n) remains relatively small compared to n. For example, a 2-digit number can be at most 99 while s(n) ≤ 81*2 = 162. In fact, as the number of digits increases, n grows exponentially while s(n) grows linearly.\nStep 3: Check the 1-digit case. Let n be a single digit a (1 ≤ a ≤ 9). Then s(n) = a². For the equality a² = a to hold, we must have a(a - 1) = 0, which implies a = 0 or a = 1. Since n must be at least 1, the only possibility is a = 1.\nStep 4: For numbers with more than one digit, testing small cases shows no solution exists because the sum of squares of digits is too small relative to the number itself (for instance, n = 15 gives s(15) = 26, which does not equal 15). Moreover, an inequality argument shows that for numbers with d ≥ 2 digits, n (which is at least 10) rapidly exceeds the maximum possible s(n).\nStep 5: Conclude that the only integer n ≥ 1 satisfying s(n) = n is n = 1.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentences about trying the new cafe downtown, Sherry waiting for a train, the mention of 574, the phrase 'succeeding', the reference to sudoku, the number 464, and the statement about the new coffee shop having the best croissants in the city.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Every minute there is a 75% chance that a train will arrive. However, if a train arrives, Sherry—who is playing sudoku—is only aware of it with a 25% chance (since she has a 75% chance of not noticing it). What is the probability that Sherry catches the train in the next five minutes?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. In any given minute, the probability that a train arrives is 0.75. If a train arrives, the probability that Sherry notices (and thus can catch) it is 0.25. Thus, the probability that she catches the train in a particular minute is 0.75 * 0.25 = 0.1875 (or 3/16).\n2. The probability that she does not catch the train in one minute is then 1 - 0.1875 = 0.8125 (or 13/16).\n3. Assuming each minute is an independent event, the probability that she does not catch the train in all five minutes is (0.8125)^5.\n4. Calculating (13/16)^5 gives (13^5)/(16^5).\n5. The probability that she catches the train at least once in the five minutes is the complement: 1 - (13/16)^5.\n6. Numerically, (0.8125)^5 is approximately 0.354, so the final probability is approximately 1 - 0.354 = 0.646.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Approximately 64.6% (or 1 - (13/16)^5).</answer>"
}

