  "solution_steps": "1. Notice that each element of the matrix is given by A(i,j) = i + j, which can be split as the sum of a function of i and a function of j. Specifically, write A(i,j) = i + j = f(i) + g(j), where f(i)=i and g(j)=j.\n2. From this, observe that the matrix A can be expressed as the sum of two rank-1 matrices. One matrix has entries i (depending only on the row), and the other has entries j (depending only on the column).\n3. The sum of two rank-1 matrices has rank at most 2. \n4. For n ≥ 2, the two component matrices are not multiples of each other, so the rank is exactly 2. Note that if n = 1, the matrix is 1×1 and its rank would be 1, but generally the interesting case is n ≥ 2.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>The rank of A is 2 (for n ≥ 2).</answer>"
