  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>At the start of a 5‑hour trip, Jill’s car odometer read 13831 km. At the end of the trip, the odometer read 464 km (after rolling over). If Jill never drove faster than 80 km/h, what is the greatest possible average speed (in km/h) she could have achieved on the trip?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Since the final odometer reading is lower than the initial reading, a rollover occurred. Let M be the modulus (the number at which the odometer resets). Then the actual distance traveled is: Distance = (M − 13831) + 464 = M − 13367.\n2. Jill never drove above 80 km/h and the trip took 5 hours. Hence, the maximum total distance she could have covered is 5 × 80 km = 400 km.\n3. To maximize her average speed, assume she drove as far as possible without ever exceeding 80 km/h. That is, we set the distance to 400 km:\n     M − 13367 = 400  →  M = 400 + 13367 = 13767.\n4. In this scenario, the trip distance is exactly 400 km, so her average speed is 400 km/5 h = 80 km/h.\n5. Because she never exceeded 80 km/h, the greatest possible average speed that is consistent with the odometer readings and the speed limit is 80 km/h.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>80 km/h</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The initial sentences about trying a new Italian restaurant and the chef arranging ingredients, as well as the numbers '947' and '887' in the description, are irrelevant to solving the math problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let f: Q → Q be a function such that for any x, y in Q, the number f(x+y) - f(x) - f(y) is an integer. Decide whether it follows that there exists a constant c such that f(x) - c·x is an integer for every rational number x.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Notice that the given property f(x+y) - f(x) - f(y) ∈ Z means that f is additive up to an integer error. In other words, f almost satisfies the additive Cauchy equation except for an integer adjustment.\n2. Consider the candidate for c: let c = f(1). Our goal is to show that for any rational number x, the difference g(x) = f(x) - c·x is always an integer.\n3. Write any rational x in the form m/n (with m ∈ Z and n ∈ N). Because f is defined on all rationals, we can express f(m/n) as a sum of f(1/n)’s. In particular, m copies of f(1/n) added together differ from f(m/n) by some integers (due to the given property applied repeatedly), hence the error remains an integer.\n4. More concretely, using the additivity condition repeatedly, for any integers m and n, the accumulated discrepancy when summing f(1/n) m times is an integer. Therefore, f(m/n) is equal to m·f(1/n) plus an integer. Similarly, because f(1) = n·f(1/n) plus an integer, it follows that f(m/n) is equal to (m/n)·f(1) plus an integer.\n5. Thus, for all rational x, we obtain f(x) - f(1)·x ∈ Z. Setting c = f(1) gives the desired result.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, such a constant exists, and one may take c = f(1).</answer>"
}
